{"title_page": "Patricia Scotland", "text_new": "{{short description|British Dominican barrister and Labour life peer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n|honorific-prefix = [[Her Excellency]] [[the Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Baroness Scotland of Asthal\n|honorific-suffix = [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] \n|image            = Patricia Scotland 2018.jpg\n|office           = 6th [[Commonwealth Secretary-General|Secretary-General of the Commonwealth of Nations]]\n|monarch          = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|term_start       = 1 April 2016\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Kamalesh Sharma]]\n|successor        = \n|office1          = [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General for England and Wales]]\n|leader1         = [[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start1      = 11 May 2010\n|term_end1        = 7 October 2011\n|predecessor1     = [[Edward Garnier]]\n|successor1       = [[Emily Thornberry]]\n|office2          = [[Attorney General for England and Wales]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start2      = 28 June 2007\n|term_end2        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor2     = [[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|The Lord Goldsmith]]\n|successor2       = [[Dominic Grieve]]\n|office3          = [[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start3      = 12 April 2010\n|term_end3        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor3     = [[Hillsborough Castle Agreement|''Office created'']]\n|successor3       = [[Dominic Grieve]]\n|office4          = [[Attorney General for Northern Ireland]]\n|primeminister4   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start4      = 28 June 2007\n|term_end4        = 12 April 2010\n|predecessor4     = [[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|The Lord Goldsmith]]\n|successor4       = [[John Larkin (Northern Ireland)|John Larkin]]\n|office5          = [[Under-Secretary of State for the Home Department|Minister of State for Criminal Justice System and Law Reforms]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start5      = 12 June 2003\n|term_end5        = 28 June 2007\n|predecessor5    = [[Charlie Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton|The Lord Falconer of Thoroton]]\n|successor5      = [[Tony McNulty]]\n|office6          = [[Lord Chancellor's Department|Parliamentary Secretary for Lord Chancellor's Department]]\n|primeminister6   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start6      = 12 June 2001\n|term_end6        = 13 June 2003\n|predecessor6    = [[Willy Bach, Baron Bach|The Lord Bach]]\n|successor6      = [[Geoffrey Filkin, Baron Filkin|The Lord Filkin]]\n|office7          = [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]]\n|primeminister7   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start7     = 28 July 1999\n|term_end7        = 12 June 2001\n|predecessor7     = [[Elizabeth Symons, Baroness Symons of Vernham Dean|The Baroness Symons]]\n|successor7       = [[Ben Bradshaw]]<br>[[Valerie Amos, Baroness Amos|The Baroness Amos]]\n|office8          = [[Member of the House of Lords]] <br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start8       = 30 October 1997<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end8         =\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1955|8|19|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Dominica]], [[British Leeward Islands]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|alma_mater       = [[Anglia Ruskin University|Mid Essex Technical College]]<br />[[University College London]]<br />[[Middle Temple]]\n}}\n'''Patricia Janet Scotland, Baroness Scotland of Asthal''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|PC|QC}} (born 19 August 1955), is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician and barrister who served in ministerial positions within the [[Her Majesty's Government|UK Government]], most notably as the  [[Attorney General for England and Wales]] and [[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]. At the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2015|2015 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]] she was elected the 6th [[Commonwealth Secretary-General|Secretary-General]] of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] and took office on 1 April 2016. She is the first woman to hold the post.<ref name=sg>{{cite news|title=Commonwealth elects first woman secretary general|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151127/local/commonwealth-elects-first-woman-secretary-general.593722|accessdate=27 November 2015|work=Times of Malta|date=27 November 2015}}</ref> She is a [[dual citizen]] of the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Dominica]], where she was born.<ref name=oz>{{cite news|title=CHOGM: Patricia Scotland is first female Commonwealth secretary-general|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/chogm-patricia-scotland-is-first-commonwealth-secretary-general/story-fn59niix-1227626361316|accessdate=28 November 2015|work=The Australian|date=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nScotland was born in [[Dominica]], the 10th child of 12 born to Roman Catholic parents,<ref>Madeleine Teahan, [https://www.exacteditions.com/read/catholic-herald/5-august-2011-9230/2/3/ \"Baroness calls for support for priests\"], ''Catholic Herald'', 5 August 2011.</ref> a Dominican mother and [[Antigua]]n father.<ref>[http://www.afr.com/brand/rear-window/alexander-downer-narrowly-avoids-commonwealth-secretarygeneral-job-20151129-glanqm< Alexander Downer narrowly avoids Commonwealth Secretary-General job], ''Financial Review'', November 29, 2015</ref> Her family emigrated to [[Walthamstow]] when she was two years old, where she attended [[Chapel End Secondary School]] and [[Walthamstow School for Girls]]. She then went on to [[Anglia Ruskin University|Mid Essex Technical College]] in [[Chelmsford]], where she obtained [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[University of London]] as an external student. She was called to the [[Bar association|bar]] at the [[Middle Temple]] in 1977, specialising in family law, and was called to the Dominican bar in 1978.<ref>[http://www.caribbean360.com/news/baroness-scotland-gets-dominicas-support-for-top-commonwealth-post \"Baroness Scotland gets Dominica\u2019s support for top Commonwealth post\"], Caribbean 360, 30 September 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Scotland became the first black woman to be appointed a [[Queen's Counsel]]. She later founded the (now closed) 1 Gray's Inn Square barristers chambers.<ref name=\"thelawyer.com\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.thelawyer.com/baroness-scotland-qc-appointed-attorney-general/126857.article|title=Baroness Scotland QC appointed attorney general|magazine=[[The Lawyer]]|date=28 June 2007|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> Early in 1997, she was elected as a [[Bencher]] of the [[Middle Temple]]. Scotland was named as a Millennium Commissioner on 17 February 1994, and was a member of the [[Commission for Racial Equality]]. She received a [[life peerage]] on a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] list of [[working peers]] and was created '''Baroness Scotland of Asthal''', of [[Asthal]] in the [[Oxfordshire|County of Oxfordshire]] on 30 October 1997.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=54938|date=4 November 1997|page=12377}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nFrom 1999 to 2001, Scotland was the [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]], where she was responsible, among others, for the UK Government's diplomatic relations with [[North America]], the [[Caribbean]], [[Overseas Territories]], [[Consular Division]], [[British Council]], administration and all Parliamentary business in the [[House of Lords]].  Scotland introduced the [[International Criminal Court Act 2001|International Criminal Court Bill]] which sought to ratify the jurisdiction of the [[International Criminal Court]] into UK law. She established the [[Pro Bono Lawyers Panel]], a panel of British-based lawyers who provided legal advice on a ''[[pro bono]]'' basis to United Kingdom nationals imprisoned in foreign countries. She created an Overseas Territories Council for the Caribbean and reformed and restructured the Foreign and Commonwealth Office's Consular Division to be able to respond more effectively to emergencies and disasters abroad such as the [[11 September attacks]].\n\nIn 2001 she became Parliamentary Secretary, [[Lord Chancellor's Department]], and was made a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]. She was the minister formally responsible for civil justice and the reform of civil law including the comprehensive reform of land registration leading to the [[Land Registration Act 2002]]. She was also formally responsible for international affairs at the Lord Chancellor's Department and was appointed by Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] as the UK Alternate Representative to the European Convention<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/patricia-scotland/26608 |title=Baroness Scotland of Asthal |publisher=Parliament.uk |date=3 June 2010 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302215610/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/patricia-scotland/26608 |archivedate=2 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and was given primary responsibility for the negotiations in relation to the Charter of Rights which were successfully concluded in 2003. During this period she consolidated the strong relations created with all the applicant countries through the FAHR programme and the member states and was subsequently awarded the Polish Medal for her contribution to the reform and development of Law in Poland.\n\nScotland was an unsuccessful hopeful contender for a [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] position in 2003, when Prime Minister Blair reportedly considered appointing her [[Leader of the House of Lords]].<ref>David Hencke, [https://www.theguardian.com/guardianpolitics/story/0,,1057438,00.html \"New Face of the Lords\"], ''The Guardian'', 7 October 2003.</ref>\n\n[[File:PatriciaScotland2a.jpg|thumb|Scotland in 2005]]\nIn 2003, Scotland was made [[Minister of State]] for the Criminal Justice System and Law Reform at the [[Home Office]] and deputy to the Home Secretary. She served in that post until 2007 under three Home Secretaries: [[David Blunkett]], [[Charles Clarke]] and [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]. While at the Home Office she was responsible for major reform of the criminal justice system. She created the Office of Criminal Justice Reform<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/inside/org/dob/direct/ocjr.html |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20050301200844/http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/inside/org/dob/direct/ocjr.html |archive-date=1 March 2005 |title=[ARCHIVED CONTENT&#93; Office for Criminal Justice Reform |publisher=Webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk |date=6 November 2009 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which helped to create and support the National Criminal Justice Board and the Local Criminal Justice Board. Having acted as Chair, she then created three Alliances to reduce re-offending (Corporate, Civic and Faith based Alliance) and the Corporate Alliance against Domestic Violence.<ref>{{cite web|author=Blue Serif - Design & Marketing Services - matt@blueserif.co.uk |url=http://www.caadv.org.uk/ |title=Corporate Alliance Against Domestic Violence |publisher=CAADV |date= |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> She created an advisory group on victims and the Criminal Justice Centre, Victims and Witness units.\n\nScotland created Inside Justice Week<ref>[http://www.justice.gov.uk/news/announcement171008a.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308021021/http://www.justice.gov.uk/news/announcement171008a.htm|date=8 March 2009}}</ref> and the Justice Awards. She introduced the Crime and Victims Act which created new offence of familial homicide which was successfully used to prosecute the killers of [[Death of Baby P|Baby P]] who would otherwise have escaped responsibility for his death.{{cn|date=June 2018}}\n\nScotland continued her responsibility for international affairs at the Home Office and continued to represent the UK in a number of international negotiations such as those relating to extradition.{{cn|date=June 2018}}\n\n===NatWest Three===\nA new [[extradition treaty]] with the [[United States|United States of America]] had been signed on 31 March 2003. Scotland had the responsibility for promoting the necessary legislation in the House of Lords.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060712/debtext/60712-0008.htm Extradition Debate], ''Hansard'', 12 July 2006.</ref> The \"[[NatWest Three]]\" extradition case made use of this treaty. The three men were British citizens, living in the UK and working for the [[Royal Bank of Scotland Group]], a British bank. On 12 July 2006, in a highly unusual move, the Speaker of the House, [[Michael Martin (politician)|Michael Martin]], allowed an emergency debate on both the treaty and the NatWest Three after a request by Liberal Democrat [[frontbencher]] [[Nick Clegg]].\n\nDuring the debate, Scotland's view in 2005 that a higher threshold to establish \"[[probable cause]]\" was required by the UK to extradite from the US than vice versa was contrasted by Clegg to comments which the Prime Minister had made in July 2006, in which he stated that the evidential burdens on the two countries were the same.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060712/debtext/60712-0004.htm UK-US Extradition Treaty], ''Hansard'', 12 July 2006: Column 1396.</ref> The NatWest Three were subsequently extradited, and accepted a [[plea-bargain]] arrangement under which they pleaded guilty to a single count of wire fraud in the United States and were sentenced to 37 months' imprisonment.\n\n===Attorney General===\n[[File:Patriciascotland.JPG|thumb|Patricia Scotland speaking at the [[Royal Courts of Justice]] before [[LGBT History Month]] (2007)]]\nOn 28 June 2007, Scotland was appointed [[Attorney General]] by Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]].<ref name=\"thelawyer.com\"/> She was the first woman to hold the office since its foundation in 1315.\n\nDuring her time as Attorney General, Scotland continued to promote ''[[pro bono]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/NewsCentre/Pages/AttorneyGeneralWelcomesProBonoProgress.aspx |title=Attorney General Welcomes Pro Bono Progress |publisher=Attorneygeneral.gov.uk |date=31 March 2010 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313112330/http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/NewsCentre/Pages/AttorneyGeneralWelcomesProBonoProgress.aspx |archivedate=13 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> work by lawyers and created an international and Schools Pro Bono Committee which was responsible for co-ordinating ''pro bono'' work. She created the Pro Bono Awards and Pro Bono Heroes. She also created the Attorney General's Youth Network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/NewsCentre/Pages/AttorneyGeneral'sYouthAdvisoryCouncilmeetsforthefirsttime.aspx |title=Attorney General's Youth Advisory Council meets for the first time |publisher=Attorneygeneral.gov.uk |date=16 December 2009 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100127074804/http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/NewsCentre/Pages/AttorneyGeneral'sYouthAdvisoryCouncilmeetsforthefirsttime.aspx |archivedate=27 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nShe was the last Attorney General for England and Wales also to be the Attorney General for Northern Ireland before the devolution of justice powers to the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]], and appointment of a separate Attorney General for Northern Ireland. She became instead Advocate General for Northern Ireland, the UK government's chief advisor on Northern Ireland law, for a brief period until Labour left office.\n\n===Shadow Attorney General===\nWhen Labour left government on 11 May 2010, Scotland became the Shadow Attorney General and was reappointed to that role by [[Ed Miliband]] when he appointed his first Shadow Cabinet in October 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.labour.org.uk/labours-new-front-bench-team |title=Ed Miliband's new frontbench team &#124; The Labour Party |publisher=.labour.org.uk |date=10 October 2011 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809174053/http://www2.labour.org.uk/labours-new-front-bench-team |archivedate=9 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She is currently{{when|date=June 2018}} a president of [[Chatham House]].<ref>[http://www.chathamhouse.org/about-us/council/baroness-scotland The Rt Hon Baroness Scotland QC - Chatham House] Retrieved 29 September 2012</ref> \n\nIn November 2012, she was appointed [[Prime Ministerial Trade Envoy]] to [[South Africa]].<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140403154217/http://www.ukti.gov.uk/uktihome/media/item/403560.html \"New Trade Envoys and Business Investment to Boost Trade Links\"], UK Trade & Investment, 12 November 2012.</ref>\n\n===Local government===\nIn December 2014, Scotland was elected as the [[Court of Aldermen|Alderman]] for the ward of [[Bishopsgate]] in the [[City of London]], having stood (in accordance with convention in the City) as an independent candidate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baroness Scotland elected as city Alderman|url=http://www.cityam.com/1418176834/baroness-scotland-elected-city-alderman|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Commonwealth Secretary-General==\n[[File:Patricia Scotland 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Scotland in 2013]]\nAt the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2015|2015 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]], Scotland was nominated for the position of [[Commonwealth Secretary-General]] by her native country of [[Dominica]] and defeated [[Antigua and Barbuda|Antiguan]] diplomat [[Ronald Sanders (diplomat)|Ronald Sanders]], who was thought to have been the frontrunner for the position,<ref name=ind>{{cite news|title=Baroness Patricia Scotland becomes first UK citizen to be elected secretary\u2011general of Commonwealth|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/baroness-patricia-scotland-becomes-first-uk-citizen-to-be-elected-secretary-general-of-commonwealth-a6752211.html|accessdate=27 November 2015|work=The Independent|date=27 November 2015}}</ref> and former [[Commonwealth Deputy Secretary-General|deputy secretary-general for political affairs]] [[Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba]] of [[Botswana]] to become the 6th Commonwealth Secretary-General and the first woman to hold the post. She began her first of a maximum of two possible four-year terms on 1 April 2016.<ref name=\"sg\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Lady Scotland vies to be next Commonwealth secretary general|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/24/lady-scotland-vying-next-commonwealth-secretary-general|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=24 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHer candidacy was opposed by [[Hugh Segal]], former Canadian special envoy to the Commonwealth and [[Senate of Canada|senator]], who wrote in an editorial that she was not qualified for the position because she \"accepted a well-paying brief from a [[Junta (governing body)|junta]] in the [[Maldives]] to argue against the Commonwealth\u2019s legitimacy when it and Canada sought the restoration of democracy in that country.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Segal|first1=Hugh|title=The spirit of the Commonwealth needs to be revived - and quickly|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/the-spirit-of-the-commonwealth-needs-to-be-revived---and-quickly/article27490483/|accessdate=November 27, 2015|work=Globe and Mail|date=November 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Former Canadian senator backs Antigua Commonwealth nominee|url=http://www.caribbeannewsnow.com/topstory-Former-Canadian-senator-backs-Antigua-Commonwealth-nominee-28475.html|accessdate=November 27, 2015|work=Caribbean News Now|date=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Illegal immigrant employment penalty===\nIn 2009 Scotland employed Lolo Tapui, an illegal immigrant. Tapui had been using a forged passport for the period up to and including December 2008. Scotland began to employ Tapui in January 2009. Tapui was later jailed for eight months for fraud, possessing a false identity stamp, and overstaying her UK visa. At her trial Tapui admitted to having been paid \u00a395,000 by the ''Daily Mail''. She was later deported to her native [[Tonga]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/apr/09/baroness-scotland-housekeeper-convicted-fraud |title=Lady Scotland's former cleaner convicted of fraud |agency=Press Association |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 April 2010 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nScotland, who was Attorney General at the time, had earlier been subjected to a penalty of \u00a35,000 for not keeping, as an employer, copies of documents used to check Tapui's immigration status, under rules Scotland helped draft as a Home Office minister. The investigation by the [[UK Border Agency]] found that Scotland did not \"knowingly\" employ an illegal worker.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/sep/27/brown-stands-by-lady-scotland |title=Brown stands by Lady Scotland as immigration row continues |agency=Press Association |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 September 2009 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Expenses controversy===\nIn November 2016 political blogger [[Paul Staines|Guido Fawkes]] published extracts from leaked documents exposing Scotland's extravagant spending on redecorating her [[grace and favour]] apartment in [[Mayfair]], [[London]]. Costs included [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]4,020 for a cupboard, \u00a35,000 for a new [[Lowboy|vanity unit]], wallpaper at a cost of \u00a310,500, \u00a35,000 on refurbishing a safe, and a ''[[Trompe-l'\u0153il]]'' style door for \u00a34,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://order-order.com/2016/11/02/1020-to-refit-baroness-scotlands-chandelier/ |title=\u00a31,200 to move Baroness Scotland's Chandelier |newspaper=Guido Fawkes |date=2 November 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nScotland denied the claims in a statement posted on the Commonwealth's website, insisting there had been \"no extravagance at all\" and explained that the spending was agreed by [[Kamalesh Sharma]], the Commonwealth's secretary-general from 2008 to 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thecommonwealth.org/media/news/secretary-general-states-case-transformative-change-commonwealth#sthash.Odb4xnlJ.dpuf |title=Secretary-General states case for transformative change at Commonwealth |newspaper=The Commonwealth |date=5 November 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/04/baroness-scotland-hits-back-at-accusations-she-oversaw-extravaga/ |title=Baroness Scotland hits back at accusations she oversaw extravagant refurbishment of official residence |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=4 November 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Contract controversy===\nIn January 2020, Scotland faced further criticism of her role as secretary-general of the Commonwealth for awarding a consultancy contract to a company run by a friend. The Audit Committee of the international organisation noted that she offered a contract to a fellow Labour peer, [[Lord Patel of Bradford]], despite his firm being \"apparently insolvent\" and \"circumventing\" the normal competitive tendering process.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51298128 |title=Baroness Scotland criticised for awarding contract to friend's firm |newspaper=BBC News |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Charitable work==\nScotland is the Patron of the Corporate Alliance Against Domestic Violence<ref>{{cite web|author=Blue Serif - Design & Marketing Services - matt@blueserif.co.uk |url=http://www.caadv.org.uk/board_patron.php |title=Baroness Scotland - (CAADV) Corporate Alliance Against Domestic Violence |publisher=CAADV |date= |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> and of [[Chineke! Orchestra|Chineke! Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Dhiren Katwa | title=Brum welcomes BAME orchestra, Chineke!| url=https://www.asian-voice.com/Culture/Music/Brum-welcomes-BAME-orchestra,-Chineke| work=Asian Voice|date=2017-09-18| accessdate=2018-12-07}}</ref> She is the joint Patron of Missio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missio.org.uk/ |title=Catholic Mission Charity |publisher=MISSIO |date= |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> a charity which is the [[Catholic Church]]'s official support organisation for overseas mission.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.missio.org.uk/mission/index.php |title=Mission |publisher=Missio.org.uk |date=18 June 1996 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430132220/http://www.missio.org.uk/mission/index.php |archivedate=30 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  She is also a patron of [[Children and Families Across Borders (CFAB)]], a charity dedicated to reuniting children who have been separated from their families.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Trustees|url=http://cfab.org.uk/about-cfab/our-trustees/|website=Children and Families Across Borders}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nScotland has been voted Peer of the Year by [[Channel 4]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/jun/28/labour.uk11|location=London|work=The Guardian|first=Mark|last=Tran|title=Profile: Lady Scotland|date=28 June 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710090515/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2007/jun/28/labour.uk11|url-status=live|archivedate=10 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[The House (magazine)|''The House'' magazine]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domnitjen.com/profiles/profile_scotlandp.html|title=Domnitjen Magazine profiles: Baroness Patricia Scotland|publisher=Domnitjen.com|date=19 August 1955|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> Parliamentarian of the Year by the Spectator<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4425550.stm|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Top politician award for Cameron|date=10 November 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060219033606/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4425550.stm|url-status=live|archivedate=19 February 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the Political Studies Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psa.ac.uk/Content.aspx?ParentID=2&SearchID=1000005|title=AWARDS|publisher=PSA|accessdate=13 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927045722/http://www.psa.ac.uk/Content.aspx?ParentID=2&SearchID=1000005|archivedate=27 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and received a number of other awards for her contribution to law reform in the UK and abroad.\n\nScotland was awarded an [[honorary degree]] from the [[University of East London]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Alumni Newsletter\">{{cite web|url= http://www.uel.ac.uk/alumni/newsletter/december2005.htm|title= UEL Alumni Newsletter|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110218234730/http://www.uel.ac.uk/alumni/newsletter/december2005.htm|archivedate= 18 February 2011|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Scotland has also been ranked the most influential Black Briton in the annual ''\"[[Powerlist]]\"'', having been ranked first in 2010, and in 2007 & 2008 when the list had separate male/female rankings. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Eboda |first1=Michael |title=The real black power list of 100 leading role models |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/aug/26/pressandpublishing.raceintheuk |website=The Observer |accessdate=22 April 2020 |date=26 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=POWERLIST 2010: BRITAIN\u2019S 100 MOST INFLUENTIAL BLACK PEOPLE |url=https://madnewsuk.com/2009/09/30/powerlist-2010-britains-100-most-influential-black-people/ |website=MAD NEWS UK |accessdate=22 April 2020 |language=en |date=30 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Black power list published |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/black-power-list-published-1794598.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=22 April 2020 |language=en |date=28 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nScotland was decreed and invested by [[Prince Carlo, Duke of Castro]], as a Dame of Merit with Star of the [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George]] in 2003. In 2014 she was appointed to the Council of the British and Irish Delegation of the Constantinian Order and promoted in rank to Dame Grand Cross of Merit.\n\nOn 1 January 2014 she was appointed [[chancellor (education)|chancellor]] of the [[University of Greenwich]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Baroness Scotland to be Chancellor of the University of Greenwich|url=http://www2.gre.ac.uk/about/news/articles/2014-news/a2825-baroness-scotland-to-be-chancellor-of-the-university-of-greenwich}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, she was listed as one of [[100 Women (BBC)|BBC's 100 Women]].<ref name=\"bbc\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-34745739|title=BBC 100 Women 2015: Who is on the list?|date=17 November 2015|work=BBC News|access-date=3 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nScotland resides in London<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/greenpolitics/immigration/6211368/Baroness-Scotland-faces-new-inquiry-call-over-170000-London-allowance.html |title=Baroness Scotland faces new inquiry call over \u00a3170,000 London allowance |newspaper=Telegraph |date=20 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924164506/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/greenpolitics/immigration/6211368/Baroness-Scotland-faces-new-inquiry-call-over-170000-London-allowance.html |archivedate=24 September 2009 }}</ref> and in [[Asthal]], where she and her husband, also a barrister, live with their two sons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/jun/28/labour.uk11|title=Profile: Lady Scotland|last=Tran|first=Mark|newspaper=Guardian|date=28 June 2007|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Scotland of Asthal Lozenge.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Azure on a Saltire Argent between four Fleur-de-lis heads outwards Or a Saltire Azure\n|supporters = On either side a Red-billed Tropic Bird proper\n|motto = Gratia In Te Est\n|badge =  Two Red-billed Tropic Birds volant in saltire proper <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20s.htm</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Patricia Scotland, Baroness Scotland of Asthal}}\n*{{UK Peer links | parliament = lords/baroness-scotland-of-asthal/2099 | hansard = ms-patricia-scotland | hansardcurr = 615 | guardian = | publicwhip = Baroness_Scotland_of_Asthal | theywork = baroness_scotland_of_asthal | record = Patricia-Scotland/1538 | bbc = 26608.stm | journalisted = patricia-scotland }}\n* [https://soundcloud.com/jawara-rawjers/baroness-patricia-scotland-with-julian-rogers Interview with Baroness Patricia Scotland] by [[Julian Rogers]]. 7 December 2014.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qz92-UpAoxg&index=2&list=PLsRNoUx8w3rOtwMTNITk2_LFPitAhP-Na \"Child of the Caribbean | Baroness Scotland | TEDxPortofSpain\"], YouTube, 17 December 2014.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales]]|years=2007\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dominic Grieve]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for Northern Ireland]]|years=2007\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Larkin (Northern Ireland)|John Larkin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]|years=2010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dominic Grieve]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edward Garnier]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]]|years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emily Thornberry]]}}\n|-\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Garry Hart, Baron Hart of Chilton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chancellor of the [[University of Greenwich]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kamalesh Sharma]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commonwealth Secretary-General|Secretary-General of the Commonwealth of Nations]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Commonwealth Secretary-General}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scotland, Patricia}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Anglia Ruskin University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University of London Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General for England and Wales]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General for Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Black British politicians]]\n[[Category:English Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:English women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Secretaries-General]]\n[[Category:Dominica emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:English people of Antigua and Barbuda descent]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Tony Blair]]\n[[Category:20th-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Middle Temple]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland Government ministers]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:People educated at Walthamstow School for Girls]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1901\u20132000]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Chatham House]]\n[[Category:People from Walthamstow]]\n[[Category:Dominica people of Antigua and Barbuda descent]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Advocates General for Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Women Law Officers of the Crown in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:BBC 100 Women]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Dominican barrister and Labour life peer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n|honorific-prefix = [[Her Excellency]] [[the Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Baroness Scotland of Asthal\n|honorific-suffix = [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|PC]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] \n|image            = Patricia Scotland 2018.jpg\n|office           = 6th [[Commonwealth Secretary-General|Secretary-General of the Commonwealth of Nations]]\n|monarch          = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|term_start       = 1 April 2016\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Kamalesh Sharma]]\n|successor        = \n|office1          = [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General for England and Wales]]\n|leader1         = [[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Ed Miliband]]\n|term_start1      = 11 May 2010\n|term_end1        = 7 October 2011\n|predecessor1     = [[Edward Garnier]]\n|successor1       = [[Emily Thornberry]]\n|office2          = [[Attorney General for England and Wales]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start2      = 28 June 2007\n|term_end2        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor2     = [[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|The Lord Goldsmith]]\n|successor2       = [[Dominic Grieve]]\n|office3          = [[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start3      = 12 April 2010\n|term_end3        = 11 May 2010\n|predecessor3     = [[Hillsborough Castle Agreement|''Office created'']]\n|successor3       = [[Dominic Grieve]]\n|office4          = [[Attorney General for Northern Ireland]]\n|primeminister4   = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start4      = 28 June 2007\n|term_end4        = 12 April 2010\n|predecessor4     = [[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|The Lord Goldsmith]]\n|successor4       = [[John Larkin (Northern Ireland)|John Larkin]]\n|office5          = [[Under-Secretary of State for the Home Department|Minister of State for Criminal Justice System and Law Reforms]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start5      = 12 June 2003\n|term_end5        = 28 June 2007\n|predecessor5    = [[Charlie Falconer, Baron Falconer of Thoroton|The Lord Falconer of Thoroton]]\n|successor5      = [[Tony McNulty]]\n|office6          = [[Lord Chancellor's Department|Parliamentary Secretary for Lord Chancellor's Department]]\n|primeminister6   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start6      = 12 June 2001\n|term_end6        = 13 June 2003\n|predecessor6    = [[Willy Bach, Baron Bach|The Lord Bach]]\n|successor6      = [[Geoffrey Filkin, Baron Filkin|The Lord Filkin]]\n|office7          = [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]]\n|primeminister7   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start7     = 28 July 1999\n|term_end7        = 12 June 2001\n|predecessor7     = [[Elizabeth Symons, Baroness Symons of Vernham Dean|The Baroness Symons]]\n|successor7       = [[Ben Bradshaw]]<br>[[Valerie Amos, Baroness Amos|The Baroness Amos]]\n|office8          = [[Member of the House of Lords]] <br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start8       = 30 October 1997<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n|term_end8         =\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1955|8|19|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Dominica]], [[British Leeward Islands]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|alma_mater       = [[Anglia Ruskin University|Mid Essex Technical College]]<br />[[University College London]]<br />[[Middle Temple]]\n}}\n'''Patricia Janet Scotland, Baroness Scotland of Asthal''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|PC|QC}} (born 19 August 1955), is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician and barrister who served in ministerial positions within the [[Her Majesty's Government|UK Government]], most notably as the  [[Attorney General for England and Wales]] and [[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]. At the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2015|2015 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]] she was elected the 6th [[Commonwealth Secretary-General|Secretary-General]] of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]] and took office on 1 April 2016. She is the first woman to hold the post.<ref name=sg>{{cite news|title=Commonwealth elects first woman secretary general|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151127/local/commonwealth-elects-first-woman-secretary-general.593722|accessdate=27 November 2015|work=Times of Malta|date=27 November 2015}}</ref> She is a [[dual citizen]] of the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Dominica]], where she was born.<ref name=oz>{{cite news|title=CHOGM: Patricia Scotland is first female Commonwealth secretary-general|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/chogm-patricia-scotland-is-first-commonwealth-secretary-general/story-fn59niix-1227626361316|accessdate=28 November 2015|work=The Australian|date=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nScotland was born in [[Dominica]], the 10th child of 12 born to Roman Catholic parents,<ref>Madeleine Teahan, [https://www.exacteditions.com/read/catholic-herald/5-august-2011-9230/2/3/ \"Baroness calls for support for priests\"], ''Catholic Herald'', 5 August 2011.</ref> a Dominican mother and [[Antigua]]n father.<ref>[http://www.afr.com/brand/rear-window/alexander-downer-narrowly-avoids-commonwealth-secretarygeneral-job-20151129-glanqm< Alexander Downer narrowly avoids Commonwealth Secretary-General job], ''Financial Review'', November 29, 2015</ref> Her family emigrated to [[Walthamstow]] when she was two years old, where she attended [[Chapel End Secondary School]] and [[Walthamstow School for Girls]]. She then went on to [[Anglia Ruskin University|Mid Essex Technical College]] in [[Chelmsford]], where she obtained [[Bachelor of Laws]] from [[University of London]] as an external student. She was called to the [[Bar association|bar]] at the [[Middle Temple]] in 1977, specialising in family law, and was called to the Dominican bar in 1978.<ref>[http://www.caribbean360.com/news/baroness-scotland-gets-dominicas-support-for-top-commonwealth-post \"Baroness Scotland gets Dominica\u2019s support for top Commonwealth post\"], Caribbean 360, 30 September 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Scotland became the first black woman to be appointed a [[Queen's Counsel]]. She later founded the (now closed) 1 Gray's Inn Square barristers chambers.<ref name=\"thelawyer.com\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.thelawyer.com/baroness-scotland-qc-appointed-attorney-general/126857.article|title=Baroness Scotland QC appointed attorney general|magazine=[[The Lawyer]]|date=28 June 2007|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> Early in 1997, she was elected as a [[Bencher]] of the [[Middle Temple]]. Scotland was named as a Millennium Commissioner on 17 February 1994, and was a member of the [[Commission for Racial Equality]]. She received a [[life peerage]] on a [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] list of [[working peers]] and was created '''Baroness Scotland of Asthal''', of [[Asthal]] in the [[Oxfordshire|County of Oxfordshire]] on 30 October 1997.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=54938|date=4 November 1997|page=12377}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nFrom 1999 to 2001, Scotland was the [[Under-Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]], where she was responsible, among others, for the UK Government's diplomatic relations with [[North America]], the [[Caribbean]], [[Overseas Territories]], [[Consular Division]], [[British Council]], administration and all Parliamentary business in the [[House of Lords]].  Scotland introduced the [[International Criminal Court Act 2001|International Criminal Court Bill]] which sought to ratify the jurisdiction of the [[International Criminal Court]] into UK law. She established the [[Pro Bono Lawyers Panel]], a panel of British-based lawyers who provided legal advice on a ''[[pro bono]]'' basis to United Kingdom nationals imprisoned in foreign countries. She created an Overseas Territories Council for the Caribbean and reformed and restructured the Foreign and Commonwealth Office's Consular Division to be able to respond more effectively to emergencies and disasters abroad such as the [[11 September attacks]].\n\nIn 2001 she became Parliamentary Secretary, [[Lord Chancellor's Department]], and was made a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]. She was the minister formally responsible for civil justice and the reform of civil law including the comprehensive reform of land registration leading to the [[Land Registration Act 2002]]. She was also formally responsible for international affairs at the Lord Chancellor's Department and was appointed by Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] as the UK Alternate Representative to the European Convention<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/patricia-scotland/26608 |title=Baroness Scotland of Asthal |publisher=Parliament.uk |date=3 June 2010 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302215610/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/patricia-scotland/26608 |archivedate=2 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and was given primary responsibility for the negotiations in relation to the Charter of Rights which were successfully concluded in 2003. During this period she consolidated the strong relations created with all the applicant countries through the FAHR programme and the member states and was subsequently awarded the Polish Medal for her contribution to the reform and development of Law in Poland.\n\nScotland was an unsuccessful hopeful contender for a [[Cabinet (government)|cabinet]] position in 2003, when Prime Minister Blair reportedly considered appointing her [[Leader of the House of Lords]].<ref>David Hencke, [https://www.theguardian.com/guardianpolitics/story/0,,1057438,00.html \"New Face of the Lords\"], ''The Guardian'', 7 October 2003.</ref>\n\n[[File:PatriciaScotland2a.jpg|thumb|Scotland in 2005]]\nIn 2003, Scotland was made [[Minister of State]] for the Criminal Justice System and Law Reform at the [[Home Office]] and deputy to the Home Secretary. She served in that post until 2007 under three Home Secretaries: [[David Blunkett]], [[Charles Clarke]] and [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]. While at the Home Office she was responsible for major reform of the criminal justice system. She created the Office of Criminal Justice Reform<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/inside/org/dob/direct/ocjr.html |archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20050301200844/http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/inside/org/dob/direct/ocjr.html |archive-date=1 March 2005 |title=[ARCHIVED CONTENT&#93; Office for Criminal Justice Reform |publisher=Webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk |date=6 November 2009 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which helped to create and support the National Criminal Justice Board and the Local Criminal Justice Board. Having acted as Chair, she then created three Alliances to reduce re-offending (Corporate, Civic and Faith based Alliance) and the Corporate Alliance against Domestic Violence.<ref>{{cite web|author=Blue Serif - Design & Marketing Services - matt@blueserif.co.uk |url=http://www.caadv.org.uk/ |title=Corporate Alliance Against Domestic Violence |publisher=CAADV |date= |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> She created an advisory group on victims and the Criminal Justice Centre, Victims and Witness units.\n\nScotland created Inside Justice Week<ref>[http://www.justice.gov.uk/news/announcement171008a.htm] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308021021/http://www.justice.gov.uk/news/announcement171008a.htm|date=8 March 2009}}</ref> and the Justice Awards. She introduced the Crime and Victims Act which created new offence of familial homicide which was successfully used to prosecute the killers of [[Death of Baby P|Baby P]] who would otherwise have escaped responsibility for his death.{{cn|date=June 2018}}\n\nScotland continued her responsibility for international affairs at the Home Office and continued to represent the UK in a number of international negotiations such as those relating to extradition.{{cn|date=June 2018}}\n\n===NatWest Three===\nA new [[extradition treaty]] with the [[United States|United States of America]] had been signed on 31 March 2003. Scotland had the responsibility for promoting the necessary legislation in the House of Lords.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060712/debtext/60712-0008.htm Extradition Debate], ''Hansard'', 12 July 2006.</ref> The \"[[NatWest Three]]\" extradition case made use of this treaty. The three men were British citizens, living in the UK and working for the [[Royal Bank of Scotland Group]], a British bank. On 12 July 2006, in a highly unusual move, the Speaker of the House, [[Michael Martin (politician)|Michael Martin]], allowed an emergency debate on both the treaty and the NatWest Three after a request by Liberal Democrat [[frontbencher]] [[Nick Clegg]].\n\nDuring the debate, Scotland's view in 2005 that a higher threshold to establish \"[[probable cause]]\" was required by the UK to extradite from the US than vice versa was contrasted by Clegg to comments which the Prime Minister had made in July 2006, in which he stated that the evidential burdens on the two countries were the same.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060712/debtext/60712-0004.htm UK-US Extradition Treaty], ''Hansard'', 12 July 2006: Column 1396.</ref> The NatWest Three were subsequently extradited, and accepted a [[plea-bargain]] arrangement under which they pleaded guilty to a single count of wire fraud in the United States and were sentenced to 37 months' imprisonment.\n\n===Attorney General===\n[[File:Patriciascotland.JPG|thumb|Patricia Scotland speaking at the [[Royal Courts of Justice]] before [[LGBT History Month]] (2007)]]\nOn 28 June 2007, Scotland was appointed [[Attorney General]] by Prime Minister [[Gordon Brown]].<ref name=\"thelawyer.com\"/> She was the first woman to hold the office since its foundation in 1315.\n\nDuring her time as Attorney General, Scotland continued to promote ''[[pro bono]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/NewsCentre/Pages/AttorneyGeneralWelcomesProBonoProgress.aspx |title=Attorney General Welcomes Pro Bono Progress |publisher=Attorneygeneral.gov.uk |date=31 March 2010 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313112330/http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/NewsCentre/Pages/AttorneyGeneralWelcomesProBonoProgress.aspx |archivedate=13 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> work by lawyers and created an international and Schools Pro Bono Committee which was responsible for co-ordinating ''pro bono'' work. She created the Pro Bono Awards and Pro Bono Heroes. She also created the Attorney General's Youth Network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/NewsCentre/Pages/AttorneyGeneral'sYouthAdvisoryCouncilmeetsforthefirsttime.aspx |title=Attorney General's Youth Advisory Council meets for the first time |publisher=Attorneygeneral.gov.uk |date=16 December 2009 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100127074804/http://www.attorneygeneral.gov.uk/NewsCentre/Pages/AttorneyGeneral'sYouthAdvisoryCouncilmeetsforthefirsttime.aspx |archivedate=27 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nShe was the last Attorney General for England and Wales also to be the Attorney General for Northern Ireland before the devolution of justice powers to the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]], and appointment of a separate Attorney General for Northern Ireland. She became instead Advocate General for Northern Ireland, the UK government's chief advisor on Northern Ireland law, for a brief period until Labour left office.\n\n===Shadow Attorney General===\nWhen Labour left government on 11 May 2010, Scotland became the Shadow Attorney General and was reappointed to that role by [[Ed Miliband]] when he appointed his first Shadow Cabinet in October 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.labour.org.uk/labours-new-front-bench-team |title=Ed Miliband's new frontbench team &#124; The Labour Party |publisher=.labour.org.uk |date=10 October 2011 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809174053/http://www2.labour.org.uk/labours-new-front-bench-team |archivedate=9 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She is currently{{when|date=June 2018}} a president of [[Chatham House]].<ref>[http://www.chathamhouse.org/about-us/council/baroness-scotland The Rt Hon Baroness Scotland QC - Chatham House] Retrieved 29 September 2012</ref> \n\nIn November 2012, she was appointed [[Prime Ministerial Trade Envoy]] to [[South Africa]].<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140403154217/http://www.ukti.gov.uk/uktihome/media/item/403560.html \"New Trade Envoys and Business Investment to Boost Trade Links\"], UK Trade & Investment, 12 November 2012.</ref>\n\n===Local government===\nIn December 2014, Scotland was elected as the [[Court of Aldermen|Alderman]] for the ward of [[Bishopsgate]] in the [[City of London]], having stood (in accordance with convention in the City) as an independent candidate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Baroness Scotland elected as city Alderman|url=http://www.cityam.com/1418176834/baroness-scotland-elected-city-alderman|accessdate=8 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Commonwealth Secretary-General==\n[[File:Patricia Scotland 2013 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|Scotland in 2013]]\nAt the [[Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2015|2015 Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting]], Scotland was nominated for the position of [[Commonwealth Secretary-General]] by her native country of [[Dominica]] and defeated [[Antigua and Barbuda|Antiguan]] diplomat [[Ronald Sanders (diplomat)|Ronald Sanders]], who was thought to have been the frontrunner for the position,<ref name=ind>{{cite news|title=Baroness Patricia Scotland becomes first UK citizen to be elected secretary\u2011general of Commonwealth|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/baroness-patricia-scotland-becomes-first-uk-citizen-to-be-elected-secretary-general-of-commonwealth-a6752211.html|accessdate=27 November 2015|work=The Independent|date=27 November 2015}}</ref> and former [[Commonwealth Deputy Secretary-General|deputy secretary-general for political affairs]] [[Mmasekgoa Masire-Mwamba]] of [[Botswana]] to become the 6th Commonwealth Secretary-General and the first woman to hold the post. She began her first of a maximum of two possible four-year terms on 1 April 2016.<ref name=\"sg\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Lady Scotland vies to be next Commonwealth secretary general|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/24/lady-scotland-vying-next-commonwealth-secretary-general|accessdate=24 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=24 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHer candidacy was opposed by [[Hugh Segal]], former Canadian special envoy to the Commonwealth and [[Senate of Canada|senator]], who wrote in an editorial that she was not qualified for the position because she \"accepted a well-paying brief from a [[Junta (governing body)|junta]] in the [[Maldives]] to argue against the Commonwealth\u2019s legitimacy when it and Canada sought the restoration of democracy in that country.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Segal|first1=Hugh|title=The spirit of the Commonwealth needs to be revived - and quickly|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-debate/the-spirit-of-the-commonwealth-needs-to-be-revived---and-quickly/article27490483/|accessdate=November 27, 2015|work=Globe and Mail|date=November 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Former Canadian senator backs Antigua Commonwealth nominee|url=http://www.caribbeannewsnow.com/topstory-Former-Canadian-senator-backs-Antigua-Commonwealth-nominee-28475.html|accessdate=November 27, 2015|work=Caribbean News Now|date=November 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\n===Illegal immigrant employment penalty===\nIn 2009 Scotland employed Lolo Tapui, an illegal immigrant. Tapui had been using a forged passport for the period up to and including December 2008. Scotland began to employ Tapui in January 2009. Tapui was later jailed for eight months for fraud, possessing a false identity stamp, and overstaying her UK visa. At her trial Tapui admitted to having been paid \u00a395,000 by the ''Daily Mail''. She was later deported to her native [[Tonga]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/apr/09/baroness-scotland-housekeeper-convicted-fraud |title=Lady Scotland's former cleaner convicted of fraud |agency=Press Association |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 April 2010 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nScotland, who was Attorney General at the time, had earlier been subjected to a penalty of \u00a35,000 for not keeping, as an employer, copies of documents used to check Tapui's immigration status, under rules Scotland helped draft as a Home Office minister. The investigation by the [[UK Border Agency]] found that Scotland did not \"knowingly\" employ an illegal worker.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/sep/27/brown-stands-by-lady-scotland |title=Brown stands by Lady Scotland as immigration row continues |agency=Press Association |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 September 2009 |accessdate=11 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Expenses controversy===\nIn November 2016 political blogger [[Paul Staines|Guido Fawkes]] published extracts from leaked documents exposing Scotland's extravagant spending on redecorating her [[grace and favour]] apartment in [[Mayfair]], [[London]]. Costs included [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]4,020 for a cupboard, \u00a35,000 for a new [[Lowboy|vanity unit]], wallpaper at a cost of \u00a310,500, \u00a35,000 on refurbishing a safe, and a ''[[Trompe-l'\u0153il]]'' style door for \u00a34,000.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://order-order.com/2016/11/02/1020-to-refit-baroness-scotlands-chandelier/ |title=\u00a31,200 to move Baroness Scotland's Chandelier |newspaper=Guido Fawkes |date=2 November 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nScotland denied the claims in a statement posted on the Commonwealth's website, insisting there had been \"no extravagance at all\" and explained that the spending was agreed by [[Kamalesh Sharma]], the Commonwealth's secretary-general from 2008 to 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thecommonwealth.org/media/news/secretary-general-states-case-transformative-change-commonwealth#sthash.Odb4xnlJ.dpuf |title=Secretary-General states case for transformative change at Commonwealth |newspaper=The Commonwealth |date=5 November 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/11/04/baroness-scotland-hits-back-at-accusations-she-oversaw-extravaga/ |title=Baroness Scotland hits back at accusations she oversaw extravagant refurbishment of official residence |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=4 November 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Contract controversy===\nIn January 2020, Scotland faced further criticism of her role as secretary-general of the Commonwealth for awarding a consultancy contract to a company run by a friend. The Audit Committee of the international organisation noted that she offered a contract to a fellow Labour peer, [[Lord Patel of Bradford]], despite his firm being \"apparently insolvent\" and \"circumventing\" the normal competitive tendering process.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51298128 |title=Baroness Scotland criticised for awarding contract to friend's firm |newspaper=BBC News |date=30 January 2020 |accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Charitable work==\nScotland is the Patron of the Corporate Alliance Against Domestic Violence<ref>{{cite web|author=Blue Serif - Design & Marketing Services - matt@blueserif.co.uk |url=http://www.caadv.org.uk/board_patron.php |title=Baroness Scotland - (CAADV) Corporate Alliance Against Domestic Violence |publisher=CAADV |date= |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> and of [[Chineke! Orchestra|Chineke! Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news | author=Dhiren Katwa | title=Brum welcomes BAME orchestra, Chineke!| url=https://www.asian-voice.com/Culture/Music/Brum-welcomes-BAME-orchestra,-Chineke| work=Asian Voice|date=2017-09-18| accessdate=2018-12-07}}</ref> She is the joint Patron of Missio,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missio.org.uk/ |title=Catholic Mission Charity |publisher=MISSIO |date= |accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> a charity which is the [[Catholic Church]]'s official support organisation for overseas mission.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.missio.org.uk/mission/index.php |title=Mission |publisher=Missio.org.uk |date=18 June 1996 |accessdate=13 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430132220/http://www.missio.org.uk/mission/index.php |archivedate=30 April 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  She is also a patron of [[Children and Families Across Borders (CFAB)]], a charity dedicated to reuniting children who have been separated from their families.<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Trustees|url=http://cfab.org.uk/about-cfab/our-trustees/|website=Children and Families Across Borders}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nScotland has been voted Peer of the Year by [[Channel 4]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/jun/28/labour.uk11|location=London|work=The Guardian|first=Mark|last=Tran|title=Profile: Lady Scotland|date=28 June 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710090515/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2007/jun/28/labour.uk11|url-status=live|archivedate=10 July 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[The House (magazine)|''The House'' magazine]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domnitjen.com/profiles/profile_scotlandp.html|title=Domnitjen Magazine profiles: Baroness Patricia Scotland|publisher=Domnitjen.com|date=19 August 1955|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> Parliamentarian of the Year by the Spectator<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4425550.stm|work=[[BBC News]]|title=Top politician award for Cameron|date=10 November 2005|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060219033606/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4425550.stm|url-status=live|archivedate=19 February 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the Political Studies Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psa.ac.uk/Content.aspx?ParentID=2&SearchID=1000005|title=AWARDS|publisher=PSA|accessdate=13 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927045722/http://www.psa.ac.uk/Content.aspx?ParentID=2&SearchID=1000005|archivedate=27 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and received a number of other awards for her contribution to law reform in the UK and abroad.\n\nScotland was awarded an [[honorary degree]] from the [[University of East London]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Alumni Newsletter\">{{cite web|url= http://www.uel.ac.uk/alumni/newsletter/december2005.htm|title= UEL Alumni Newsletter|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110218234730/http://www.uel.ac.uk/alumni/newsletter/december2005.htm|archivedate= 18 February 2011|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Scotland has also been ranked the most influential Black Briton in the annual ''\"[[Powerlist]]\"'', having been ranked first in 2010, and in 2007 & 2008 when the list had seperate male/female rankings. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Eboda |first1=Michael |title=The real black power list of 100 leading role models |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/aug/26/pressandpublishing.raceintheuk |website=The Observer |accessdate=22 April 2020 |date=26 August 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=POWERLIST 2010: BRITAIN\u2019S 100 MOST INFLUENTIAL BLACK PEOPLE |url=https://madnewsuk.com/2009/09/30/powerlist-2010-britains-100-most-influential-black-people/ |website=MAD NEWS UK |accessdate=22 April 2020 |language=en |date=30 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Black power list published |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/black-power-list-published-1794598.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=22 April 2020 |language=en |date=28 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nScotland was decreed and invested by [[Prince Carlo, Duke of Castro]], as a Dame of Merit with Star of the [[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George]] in 2003. In 2014 she was appointed to the Council of the British and Irish Delegation of the Constantinian Order and promoted in rank to Dame Grand Cross of Merit.\n\nOn 1 January 2014 she was appointed [[chancellor (education)|chancellor]] of the [[University of Greenwich]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Baroness Scotland to be Chancellor of the University of Greenwich|url=http://www2.gre.ac.uk/about/news/articles/2014-news/a2825-baroness-scotland-to-be-chancellor-of-the-university-of-greenwich}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, she was listed as one of [[100 Women (BBC)|BBC's 100 Women]].<ref name=\"bbc\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-34745739|title=BBC 100 Women 2015: Who is on the list?|date=17 November 2015|work=BBC News|access-date=3 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nScotland resides in London<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/greenpolitics/immigration/6211368/Baroness-Scotland-faces-new-inquiry-call-over-170000-London-allowance.html |title=Baroness Scotland faces new inquiry call over \u00a3170,000 London allowance |newspaper=Telegraph |date=20 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924164506/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/greenpolitics/immigration/6211368/Baroness-Scotland-faces-new-inquiry-call-over-170000-London-allowance.html |archivedate=24 September 2009 }}</ref> and in [[Asthal]], where she and her husband, also a barrister, live with their two sons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/jun/28/labour.uk11|title=Profile: Lady Scotland|last=Tran|first=Mark|newspaper=Guardian|date=28 June 2007|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Scotland of Asthal Lozenge.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Azure on a Saltire Argent between four Fleur-de-lis heads outwards Or a Saltire Azure\n|supporters = On either side a Red-billed Tropic Bird proper\n|motto = Gratia In Te Est\n|badge =  Two Red-billed Tropic Birds volant in saltire proper <ref>http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/lp1958%20s.htm</ref>}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Patricia Scotland, Baroness Scotland of Asthal}}\n*{{UK Peer links | parliament = lords/baroness-scotland-of-asthal/2099 | hansard = ms-patricia-scotland | hansardcurr = 615 | guardian = | publicwhip = Baroness_Scotland_of_Asthal | theywork = baroness_scotland_of_asthal | record = Patricia-Scotland/1538 | bbc = 26608.stm | journalisted = patricia-scotland }}\n* [https://soundcloud.com/jawara-rawjers/baroness-patricia-scotland-with-julian-rogers Interview with Baroness Patricia Scotland] by [[Julian Rogers]]. 7 December 2014.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Qz92-UpAoxg&index=2&list=PLsRNoUx8w3rOtwMTNITk2_LFPitAhP-Na \"Child of the Caribbean | Baroness Scotland | TEDxPortofSpain\"], YouTube, 17 December 2014.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales]]|years=2007\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dominic Grieve]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for Northern Ireland]]|years=2007\u20132010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Larkin (Northern Ireland)|John Larkin]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Advocate General for Northern Ireland]]|years=2010}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dominic Grieve]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Edward Garnier]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Attorney General for England and Wales|Shadow Attorney General]]|years=2010\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Emily Thornberry]]}}\n|-\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Garry Hart, Baron Hart of Chilton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chancellor of the [[University of Greenwich]]|years=2014\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kamalesh Sharma]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Commonwealth Secretary-General|Secretary-General of the Commonwealth of Nations]]|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Commonwealth Secretary-General}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scotland, Patricia}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Anglia Ruskin University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University of London Worldwide]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General for England and Wales]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General for Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Black British politicians]]\n[[Category:English Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:English women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Secretaries-General]]\n[[Category:Dominica emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:English people of Antigua and Barbuda descent]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Tony Blair]]\n[[Category:20th-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Middle Temple]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland Government ministers]]\n[[Category:People associated with the University of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:People educated at Walthamstow School for Girls]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1901\u20132000]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Chatham House]]\n[[Category:People from Walthamstow]]\n[[Category:Dominica people of Antigua and Barbuda descent]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Advocates General for Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Women Law Officers of the Crown in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:BBC 100 Women]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: seperate->separate", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patricia_Scotland"}
{"title_page": "Peter Beard", "text_new": "{{short description|American photographer and writer}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peter Beard\n| image              = PeterBeardGiraffes-HogRanch2014-wiki.jpg\n| caption            = Beard in 2014\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1938|01|22|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = New York, United States\n| disappeared_place  = March 31, 2020<br />[[Montauk, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{circa}} March 31/April 2020<br />(aged 82)\n| death_place        = [[Montauk Point, New York]], U.S. \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = [[Camp Hero State Park]]<br />April 19, 2020\n|nationality         = American\n| education          = [[Pomfret School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Yale University]]\n| occupation         = [[Artist]]\n| title              = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman|1967|1970|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Cheryl Tiegs]]|1981|1983|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|Nejma Khanum|1986|2020|end=his death}}\n| children           = 1\n| website            = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n\n'''Peter Hill Beard''' (January 22, 1938 &ndash; March/April 2020) was an American artist, [[photographer]], [[diarist]], and writer who lived and worked in New York City, [[Montauk, New York|Montauk]] and Kenya.  His photographs of Africa, [[African animals]] and the journals that often integrated his photographs, have been widely shown and published since the 1960s.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nPeter Beard was born in 1938 as a New York heir to a railroad fortune on his mother's side of the family and a tobacco inheritance on his father's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/peter-beard-2013-3/index1.html|title=Taming Peter Beard|website=NYMag.com|access-date=2018-01-08}}</ref> He was raised in New York City, [[Alabama]], and [[Islip, New York|Islip]], [[Long Island]], Beard began keeping diaries as a young boy and making photographs, as an extension of the diaries, at the age of 12.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref> A graduate of [[Pomfret School]], he entered [[Yale University]] in 1957, with the intention of pursuing pre-med studies, only to switch his major to [[art history]]. At Yale, he was tapped into the secret society [[Scroll and Key]]. His mentors at Yale included [[Josef Albers]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]] and [[Vincent Scully]]. Beard graduated with an [[A.B.]] in 1961.\n\nInspired by earlier trips to Africa in both 1955 and 1960, Beard traveled to [[Kenya]] upon graduation. Working at [[Tsavo Conservation Area|Tsavo National Park]], he photographed and documented the demise of 35,000 [[elephant]]s and other wildlife, later to become the subject of his first book, ''The End of the Game''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=The End of the Game|date=1965|publisher=Viking Press|location=New York|isbn=978-3-8365-0530-7}}</ref>  During this time, Beard acquired Hog Ranch, a property near the [[Ngong Hills]] adjacent to the coffee farm owned by [[Karen Blixen]] (pen name Isak Dinesen), which would become his lifelong home-base in [[East Africa]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n==Art==\n\nBeard's photographs of Africa, African animals and journals that often integrate his photographs have been widely shown and published since the 1970s. Each of his works is unique, a combination of his photography with elements derived from his daily diary-keeping, a practice he continued until his death in 2020. These volumes contain newspaper clippings, dried leaves, insects, old [[Photographic print toning#Sepia toning|sepia]]-toned photos, transcribed telephone messages, [[marginalia]] in [[India ink]], photographs of women, quotes, found objects, and the like; these become incorporated, with original drawings and collage by Beard. Certain of his works incorporate animal blood, sometimes Beard's own blood (in sparing quantities), a painting medium the artist favored.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Enright|first1=Robert|title=The Consummate Fragmentarian|journal=Modern Painters Magazine|date=2002}}</ref>\n\nHe was a photographer for magazines including [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] and [[Elle (magazine)|Elle]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Fox|first=Margalit|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/peter-beard-dead.html|title=Peter Beard, Wildlife Photographer on the Wild Side, Dies at 82|date=2020-04-19|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-20|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe Peter Beard Studio and Archive was started by Peter and Nejma Beard, and is the primary source for artwork by Peter Beard.&nbsp; The Archive maintains a repository of published and unpublished written and visual material relating to the artist's life, work, projects, travels, exhibitions, and relations with his cohort.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nBeard's first exhibition was at the Blum Helman Gallery, New York City, in 1975.  Landmark museum exhibitions have been held at the [[International Center of Photography]], New York City, in 1977, and the [[Centre national de la photographie]], Paris, in 1997. Gallery exhibitions followed in Berlin, London, Toronto, Madrid, Milan, Tokyo and Vienna. Beard's work is included in private collections throughout the world.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> \n\nIn 2017, Beard was sued by actor [[David Spade]], who purchased one of his works. Spade tried to resell a Peter Beard photograph that he had purchased from dealer [[Peter Tunney]], but the unsigned work could not be authenticated.<ref name=artnet>{{cite news |last=Kinsella|first= Eileen|date=February 3, 2017 |title=Actor David Spade Sues Photographer Peter Beard for Failure to Authenticate a Work |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/david-spade-sues-photographer-peter-beard-844637 |newspaper=Artnet.com|access-date=February 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nDescended from distinguished American families on both sides, Beard was one of three sons born to Roseanne Hoar Beard and Anson McCook Beard, Jr.  A great-grandfather, [[James Jerome Hill]], was founder of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] in the [[United States]] in the late 19th/early 20th centuries. Having made his fortune in the railroad business, James Jerome Hill was a great patron of the arts.  All of his heirs were exposed to and owned great collections, presumably having a strong influence on Beard's interests in the arts and beauty.<ref name=\"Vanamee\">{{cite news  |url=https://www.yahoo.com/lifestyle/peter-beard-romanced-lee-radziwill-114700232.html |work=[[Town & Country (magazine)|Town & Country]] |title=Peter Beard Romanced Lee Radziwill and Partied with the Rolling Stones. He Was Also a True Original |first1=Norman |last1=Vanamee |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBeard found marriage to be constricting:<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/1996/11/beard199611|title=African Dreamer|first=Leslie|last=Bennetts|website=Vanity Fair}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|The institution of marriage should be re-examined because of its overwhelming claustrophobia. The odds are stacked against spontaneity and effervescence. It's an institution that was brought about for the sake of family and children, but biologically it's very unnatural. It's masochism and torture the way it's been organized.}}\n\nHe nonetheless married three times. His first wife was Mary \"Minnie\" Olivia Cochran Cushing (later Mrs James J. Coleman Jr.),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/james-coleman-obituary-3g58vbv2s|title=James Coleman obituary|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref> a society figure, granddaughter of artist [[Howard Gardiner Cushing]], and a former assistant to the fashion designer [[Oscar de la Renta]].<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=http://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/08/13/106222996.html?pageNumber=74|title=Minnie Cushing and Peter Beard Wed in Newport; A Bridal Party of 21 Attend Couple at Historic Church Twin Flower Girls|website=timesmachine.nytimes.com}}</ref> They married in 1967 in Newport, Rhode Island<ref name=\"auto4\"/> and divorced three years later.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/11/09/archives/the-self-described-pathetic-person-they-all-want-to-be-with.html |title=The Self\u2010Described \u2018Pathetic Person\u2019 |first=Judy |last=Klemesrud |date=November 9, 1975 |via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nNext he was married to [[Cheryl Tiegs]] (formerly married to Stanley John Dragoti), the fashion model, from 1981 to 1984.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/nature-lovers-peter-beard-and-cheryl-tiegs-leave-wildlife-behind-for-the-newlywed-game-vol-15-no-22/ |title=Nature Lovers Peter Beard and Cheryl Tiegs Leave Wildlife Behind for the Newlywed Game |website=PEOPLE.com}}</ref><ref>Gross, Michael, \"The Dawn of the Supermodel\", New York Magazine, Apr 3, 1995, pp 40+</ref>\n\nHis last wife was Nejma Khanum, a daughter of an Afghan judge, whom he married in Kenya in 1986.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/news/features/peter-beard-2013-3/|title=Photographer Peter Beard\u2019s Legacy |website=New York Magazine}}</ref> The couple had one child, a daughter, Zara (born 1988),<ref name=\"auto3\"/> for whom his book, ''Zara's Tales,''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa|date=2004|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-679-42659-0|url=https://archive.org/details/zarastalesfromho00bear}}</ref> was written.\n\nIn 1996, he was charged by an elephant and gored in the right leg. After arriving at the hospital without a pulse, he was revived, and survived.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/peter-beard-dead.html|title=Peter Beard, Wildlife Photographer on the Wild Side, Dies at 82|first=Margalit|last=Fox|date=April 19, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Alec Baldwin with Peter Beard: The Elephant Attack |url=https://www.americansuburbx.com/2016/01/alec-baldwin-with-peter-beard-the-elephant-attack.html |date=January 2016 |website=American Suburb X}}</ref>\n\nBeard befriended and in some cases collaborated with many artists, including [[Andy Warhol]], [[Andrew Wyeth]], [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], [[Karen Blixen]], [[Truman Capote]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]], and [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. He also photographed many other well-known people.<ref name=\"auto2\"/> He appeared in [[Adolfas Mekas]]'s film, ''[[Hallelujah the Hills (film)|Hallulujah the Hills]]'', in 1963, at the first [[New York Film Festival]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Death==\nOn the afternoon of March 31, 2020 Beard, who was suffering from [[dementia]] and ill health after a [[stroke]], wandered away from his [[Montauk, Long Island]] home. Despite exhaustive searches he was not found.<ref> Peter Beard Missing, Search Underway in Montauk [https://www.easthamptonstar.com/police-courts/202041/peter-beard-missing-search-underway-montauk]</ref>\n\nOn April 19 Beard's body was found by a hunter in a densely wooded area in [[Camp Hero State Park]] in [[Montauk Point, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stowe |first1=Stacey |title=Peter Beard\u2019s Family Confirms His Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/design/peter-beard-found-montauk.amp.html |website=The New York Times |publisher=nytimes.com |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> As of April 20 a cause of death had not been determined.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fox |first1=Margalit |title=Peter Beard, Wildlife Photographer on the Wild Side, Dies at 82 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/peter-beard-dead.amp.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=nytimes.com |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/wildlife-photographer-peter-beard-found-181054078.html |title=Celebrity Wildlife photographer Peter Beard found dead near his home |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=April 20, 2020 |via=[[Yahoo!]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Featured !! Director !! Producer !! Editor !! Other\n|-\n| 2017 || ''That Summer'' || Yes || No || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Making of the 2009 Pirelli Calendar'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1994 || ''Montauk Diaries'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1988 || ''Last Word from Paradise: With Peter Beard in Africa'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1980 || ''Japanese Long Line Tuna Fishing'' || No || No || No || No || Introducer \n|-\n| 1979 || ''Africa: The End of the Game'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1976 || ''The Bicentennial Big Foot Blues'' || No || Yes || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 1975-76 || ''Longing for Darkness'' || No || No || Yes || Yes || No \n|-\n| 1972 || ''Sisters'' (working title) || Yes || Yes || Yes || No || Initiated\n|-\n| 1963 || ''[[Hallelujah the Hills (film)|Hallelujah the Hills]]'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|}\n\n==Publications==\n===Selected books===\n\n* Graham, Alistair, and Beard, Peter (1973). Eyelids of Morning: The Mingled Destinies of Crocodiles and Men. Greenwich, CT: New York Graphic Society. {{ISBN|0-8212-0464-5}}\n* Beard, Peter; and Gatura, Kamante (1975). Longing for Darkness: Kamante's Tales from Out of Africa. New York: Harcourt Brace Jovanovich. {{ISBN|0-15-153080-7}}\n* Beard, Peter (2004). Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa. New York: Knopf. {{ISBN|0-679-42659-0}}\n* Beard, Peter (1965). The End of the Game. New York: Viking Press.  Reprinted New York: Doubleday, 1977.  Japan: Camera Manichi, 1978.  Germany: Taschen, 2008.  {{ISBN|978-3-8365-0530-7}