 in Rhode Island\n| width           = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| image_upright   = \n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| location        = [[Rhode Island]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island]], U.S.\n| arrival_date    = \n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 5,841\n| suspected_cases = \n| severe_cases    = \n| recovery_cases  = 293 <small>(hospital discharges)</small><ref name=\"doh415\"/>\n| deaths          = 181\n| territories     = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n| hospitalized_cases = 270 (current)\n| critical_cases  = 71 current)\n| ventilator_cases = 44 (current)\n}}\nThe 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Rhode Island]] is part of an ongoing worldwide [[Viral disease|viral]] [[pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus&nbsp;2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}). As of April 22, 2020, there are 5,841 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Rhode Island, 270 of which are hospitalized, and 181 reported deaths.<ref name=\"doh415\"/>\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Rhode Island medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n\n===March===\n{{prose|date=April 2020}}\n* '''March 1:''' The first two confirmed positive cases of coronavirus in Rhode Island are identified. Both patients are connected to a [[St. Raphael Academy]] school trip to Italy that had occurred in February.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Press |first1=Associated |title=2 cases of COVID-19 virus confirmed in Rhode Island |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/01/first-virus-case-confirmed-in-rhode-island/ |website=Press Herald |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 9:''' Governor [[Gina Raimondo]] declares a state of emergency.<ref>{{cite news |last=Miller |first=G. Wayne |date=March 9, 2020 |title=Raimondo declares state of emergency in R.I. over coronavirus |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200309/raimondo-declares-state-of-emergency-in-ri-over-coronavirus |work=Providence Journal |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 11:''' The [[University of Rhode Island]] cancels all in-person classes through April 3, with classes resuming online on March 23.<ref>{{cite web |title=URI: No on-campus classes through at least April 3 due to coronavirus |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/uri-no-on-campus-classes-through-at-least-april-3-due-to-coronavirus/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 12:''' [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]] mayor [[Jorge Elorza]] postpones all public city meetings and pulls all entertainment licenses in the city, effectively closing all clubs, music venues, and movie theaters.<ref>{{cite web |last1=List |first1=Madeleine |title=Providence mayor issues state of emergency, revokes entertainment licenses |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200312/providence-mayor-issues-state-of-emergency-revokes-entertainment-licenses |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* '''March 13:''' \n** Students at Springbrook Elementary School in [[Westerly, Rhode Island|Westerly]] self-quarantine after a student tests positive.<ref>{{cite news |last=Doiron |first=Sarah |date=March 13, 2020 |title=Police: Westerly child with COVID-19 received autograph from infected Jazz player during Celtics game |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/police-westerly-child-with-covid-19-received-autograph-from-infected-jazz-player-during-celtics-game/ |work=WPRI |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>  The child had received an autograph from [[Utah Jazz]] player [[Rudy Gobert]], who had also tested positive, at a [[Boston Celtics]] game earlier in the month.<ref>{{cite web |title=Child who tested positive for Coronavirus got Rudy Gobert's autograph last week |url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2020/03/13/child-with-coronavirus-autograph-from-jazz/ |website=ProBasketballTalk {{!}} NBC Sports |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n** Students at [[Cranston High School West]] self-quarantine for two weeks after a student tests positive.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reynolds |first1=Mark |title=Cranston West student tests positive for coronavirus; students, teachers told to self-quarantine |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200313/cranston-west-student-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-students-teachers-told-to-self-quarantine |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n** [[Twin River Casino]] in [[Lincoln, Rhode Island|Lincoln]] and Tiverton Casino in [[Tiverton, Rhode Island|Tiverton]] are closed for one week, which is later extended indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web |title=Twin River and Tiverton casinos to remain closed until further notice |url=https://www.abc6.com/twin-river-and-tiverton-casinos-to-remain-closed-until-further-notice/ |website=ABC6 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Staff |first1=Journal |title=Twin River casinos to close for one week |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200313/twin-river-casinos-to-close-for-one-week |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> \n** The St. Patrick's Day parade in [[Newport, Rhode Island|Newport]] is canceled for the first time in its 64-year history due to coronavirus concerns.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thatcher |first1=Rachael |title=First cancellation in history of Newport St. Patrick's Day parade evokes understanding, disappointment |url=https://www.newportri.com/news/20200313/first-cancellation-in-history-of-newport-st-patricks-day-parade-evokes-understanding-disappointment |website=The Newport Daily News |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** [[WSBE-TV]], the [[PBS]] affiliate for Rhode Island, cancels the production of all local programming until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Paul Edward |title=Rhode Island PBS halts production due to coronavirus |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200313/rhode-island-pbs-halts-production-due-to-coronavirus |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''March 16:'''\n**  Public schools are closed onward.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nesi |first=Ted |date=March 13, 2020 |title=RI public schools closed next week; 9 new coronavirus cases identified |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/friday-afternoon-coronavirus-update-rhode-island/ |work=WPRI |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Providence]] cancels all public [[Mass in the Catholic Church|Mass]] services until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=DaSilva |first1=Melanie |title=Providence, Fall River Dioceses suspend all public Masses |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/diocese-of-providence-suspending-all-public-masses/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Preservation Society of Newport County]] closes all of its mansion properties to public tours.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus related cancellations, postponements and updates in Newport County for March 14\u201315 |url=https://www.newportri.com/news/20200314/coronavirus-related-cancellations-postponements-and-updates-in-newport-county-for-march-14-15 |website=The Newport Daily News |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''March 17:'''\n**  Bars and dine-in restaurants closed, crowds of 25 or more people banned.<ref>{{cite news |last=Miller |first=G. Wayne |date=March 16, 2020 |title=Raimondo shutting dine-in restaurants, bars for 2 weeks; 'community spread' of virus now seen in R.I. |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200316/raimondo-shutting-dine-in-restaurants-bars-for-2-weeks-rsquocommunity-spreadrsquo-of-virus-now-seen-in-ri |work=Providence Journal |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> \n** The [[Providence Place]] shopping mall is closed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus In Rhode Island: No Dine-In At Restaurants, Providence Place Mall Closed |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2020/03/16/coronavirus-rhode-island-restaurants-providence-place-mall/ |website=CBS Boston |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> \n** The [[Rhode Island Public Transit Authority]] closes its facilities at [[Kennedy Plaza]] in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]].<ref>{{cite web |title=RIPTA: Kennedy Plaza closed to prevent large crowds |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/ripta-kennedy-plaza-transport-center-closed-to-prevent-large-crowds/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n** All state public libraries are closed through March 22, later extended to April 3.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ocean State Libraries Responds to COVID-19 \u2013 Ocean State Libraries |url=https://www.oslri.org/osl-responds-covid-19/ |website=Ocean State Libraries |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Library Closings \u2013 Ocean State Libraries |url=https://www.oslri.org/library-closings/ |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n** There were 23 confirmed cases by March 17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pbn.com/2-new-covid-19-cases-identified-r-i-businesses-to-receive-assistance/|title=2 new COVID-19 cases identified; R.I. businesses to receive assistance|first=James|last=Bessette|date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> \n*'''March 18:''' The [[Trinity Repertory Company]] in Providence cancels the remainder of its 2019-20 theater season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Trinity Rep Announces Cancellation Of Remainder Of 2019-20 Season |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/rhode-island/article/Trinity-Rep-Announces-Cancellation-Of-Remainder-Of-2019-20-Season-20200318 |website=BroadwayWorld.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''March 20:''' \n** The [[Rhode Island National Guard]] is activated to assist the state with the crisis by delivering food and staffing testing centers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rhode Island up to 54 COVID-19 cases; National Guard fully activated |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/rhode-island-up-to-54-covid-19-cases/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Restaurants are allowed by the state to sell beer and wine for take-out orders to supplement their income while dine-in services are suspended.<ref>{{cite web |title=RI to let restaurants sell takeout beer, wine amid COVID-19 crisis |url=https://www.wpri.com/news/ri-to-let-restaurants-sell-takeout-beer-wine-amid-covid-19-crisis/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 22:'''\n** Eighty-three confirmed cases by March 22.<ref name=\"wpri322\">{{cite web |last1=Sherman |first1=Eli |last2=Nesi |first2=Ted |last3=Kalunian |first3=Kim |title=83 total COVID-19 cases in RI; Gov. orders additional business closures |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/raimondo-covid-19-update-sunday/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n** The state orders all entertainment and recreation businesses, barber shops, hair salons, and tattoo shops to close.<ref name=\"wpri322\"/>\n*'''March 23:''' \n** All state public schools resume classes through [[distance education]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cullinane |first1=Ashley |title=Distance learning begins for Rhode Island students |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/distance-learning-begins-for-rhode-island-students |website=WJAR |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[2020 Rhode Island Democratic primary]] is postponed from April 28 to June 2.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregg |first1=Katherine |title=Raimondo orders R.I. primary postponement |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200323/raimondo-orders-ri-primary-postponement |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''March 24:''' \n** [[New Shoreham, Rhode Island|New Shoreham]] issues a shelter-in-place order for [[Block Island]] effective March 24 through April 15.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shelter-in-place order issued for Block Island|first=Shaun|last=Towne|publisher=[[WPRI-TV]]|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 24, 2020|url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/shelter-in-place-order-issued-on-block-island/}}</ref>\n** The three towns located on [[Aquidneck Island]] - Newport, [[Middletown, Rhode Island|Middletown]], and [[Portsmouth, Rhode Island|Portsmouth]] - all implement shelter-in-place orders and require all out-of-state or seasonal residents to quarantine for 14 days upon their arrival.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Richmond |first1=Will |title=All 3 Aquidneck Island communities call for visitors to self-quarantine as people are 'flocking' to second homes |url=https://www.newportri.com/news/20200324/all-3-aquidneck-island-communities-call-for-visitors-to-self-quarantine-as-people-are-lsquoflockingrsquo-to-second-homes |website=The Newport Daily News |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**  The University of Rhode Island cancels its graduation commencement ceremony scheduled for May 16 and 17.<ref>{{cite web |title=URI nixes in-person commencement ceremonies, seeking alternative celebrations |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/uri-nixes-in-person-commencement-ceremonies-looks-for-alternative-celebration-ideas/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Brown University]] in Providence postpones its graduation commencement ceremony, which was scheduled for May, until the fall.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Borg |first1=Linda |title=Brown University postpones commencement |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200324/brown-university-postpones-commencement |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** Travelers entering Rhode Island from [[T. F. Green Airport]] are required to self-quarantine for 14 days.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gammans |first1=Bay |title=Travelers arriving at TF Green now greeted by National Guard, ordered to self-quarantine |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/travelers-arriving-at-tf-green-now-greeted-by-national-guard-ordered-to-self-quarantine/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 25:''' The [[Rhode Island Air National Guard]] cancels its annual air show, which was scheduled to take place at the [[Quonset State Airport]] in [[North Kingstown, Rhode Island|North Kingstown]] in June.<ref>{{cite web |last1=NEWS |first1=NBC 10 |title=Rhode Island National Guard cancels 2020 air show |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/rhode-island-national-guard-cancels-2020-air-show |website=WJAR |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*'''March 26:''' \n** Governor Raimondo announces that any individual coming to the state from [[New York (state)|New York]] by land or air that plans to stay in Rhode Island must self-quarantine for 14 days.<ref name=\"wpri25\">{{cite web |title=RI has 33 new cases of COVID-19; travelers from NY ordered to self-quarantine |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/march-26-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Rhode Island State Police]] establish a checkpoint on [[Interstate 95 in Rhode Island|Interstate 95]] at the Connecticut border, at which motorists with New York license plates and who plan to stay in the state are required to give their contact information.<ref>{{cite web |title=RI State Police, National Guard set up checkpoint to stop, log travelers from NY |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/ri-state-police-national-guard-set-up-checkpoint-to-stop-log-travelers-from-ny/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n** Raimondo orders grocery stores to limit the number of customers in their building at once to 25% of stated fire capacity.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rhode Island shoppers experiencing new restrictions at retail and grocery stores |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/rhode-island-shoppers-experiencing-new-restrictions-at-retail-and-grocery-stores |website=WJAR |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n* '''March 27:''' \n** Raimondo extends several gathering bans through April and May, including a ban on dine-in service at restaurants through April 13. Entertainment, recreational and \"close-contact\" businesses (such as barber shops) are also ordered closed through April 13.<ref name=\"wpri27\">{{cite web |title=RI has 38 new cases of COVID-19; National Guard to go door-to-door looking for NY travelers |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/march-27-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> \n** 203 total confirmed cases by March 27, 28 of whom are hospitalized.<ref name=\"wpri27\"/>\n* '''March 28:''' \n** Rhode Island reports its first two deaths from the coronavirus: One individual in their 80s who died on March 27, and another individual in their 70s who died on March 28, both of whom had underlying medical conditions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Paul Edward |title=R.I. reports first coronavirus deaths |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200328/ri-reports-first-coronavirus-deaths |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** Governor Raimondo enacts a \"stay at home\" order for all Rhode Islanders who are not travelling to purchase food, household supplies, medicine, or gasoline, or are going for a recreational walk alone.<ref name=\"wpri28\">{{cite web |last1=Sherman |first1=Eli |title=RI announces first two COVID-19 deaths; Raimondo issues stay-at-home order |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/ri-announces-first-two-deaths-related-to-covid-19/ |website=WPRI |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n**  Raimondo also announces that any individual travelling to the state from anywhere outside of Rhode Island for non-work purposes are required to quarantine at home for 14 days.<ref name=\"wpri28\"/> Individuals who live in Rhode Island but work outside of the state are also required to quarantine when they are not at work.<ref name=\"wpri28\"/> This legislation replaces the executive order that affected only travelers to New York, which was repealed by Governor Raimondo.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Raimondo |first1=Gina |title=Executive Order 20-14 |url=http://www.governor.ri.gov/documents/orders/Executive-Order-20-14.pdf |website=Office of the Governor of Rhode Island |accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref>\n** Gatherings in the state are further restricted, with any gathering of over five people banned.<ref name=\"wpri28\"/>\n** Raimondo orders all \"non essential\" retail to close until April 13.<ref name=\"projo28\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=G. Wayne |title=As first 2 R.I. coronavirus deaths announced, Gov. Raimondo enacts sweeping restrictions |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200328/with-first-2-ri-coronavirus-deaths-raimondo-issues-stay-at-home-order-closes-non-essential-retail |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The Rhode Island Department of Business Regulation issues a list of stores that will be allowed to remain open, including supermarkets, convenience stores, farmers' markets, food banks and pantries, specialty food stores, pharmacies, liquor stores, [[Cannabis dispensaries in the United States|medical cannabis dispensaries]], mail delivery operations, printing shops and operations, pet supply stores, laundromats, gas stations, electronics stores, hardware stores, automobile supply stores, gun shops, funeral homes, banks, healthcare uniform stores, and restaurants offering take-out or delivery.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sherman |first1=Eli |title=Liquor stores? Gun shops? Here are the essential businesses that can stay open in RI |url=https://www.wpri.com/target-12/liquor-stores-gun-shops-here-are-the-essential-businesses-that-can-stay-open-in-ri/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Non-essential retailers, such as book stores and clothing stores, are allowed to continue to receive and send orders made online or by telephone.<ref>{{cite web |title=R.I. posts list of 'critical retail businesses' |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200328/ri-posts-list-of-rsquocritical-retail-businessesrsquo |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**Police and national guard members knocked on doors of homes where cars had New York license plates to remind them of a requirement to self-quarantine.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/coronavirus-trump-decides-against-quarantine-york-region-020137905.html Coronavirus: Trump decides against quarantine of New York region] by Paul HANDLEY, AFP, 28 Mar 2020</ref>\n* '''March 29:''' \n** The state suspends all child care licences through April 3.<ref name=\"projo29\">{{cite web |last1=Staff |first1=Journal |title=3rd death in R.I. from coronavirus; 55 new cases |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200329/3rd-death-in-ri-from-coronavirus-55-new-cases |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** Following public comments by New York governor [[Andrew Cuomo]], Governor Raimondo and Rhode Island State Police colonel James Manni clarify the wording of the Mar. 28 order, reiterating that all out-of-state passenger vehicles that are planning to stay in Rhode Island are required to visit information centers on the Rhode Island-Connecticut border to collect quarantine information before quarantining in their homes for 14 days.<ref name=\"wpri29\">{{cite web |title=RI reports 3rd COVID-19 death; 55 new cases Sunday |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/march-29-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=29 March 2020}}</ref> The order does not affect passenger vehicles who are passing through Rhode Island to another state, commuters, or individuals who cross the border to purchase groceries.<ref name=\"wpri29\"/>\n* '''March 30:''' Raimondo announces Rhode Island school buildings will be closed through the end of April, with classes continuing through distance learning.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Borg |first1=Linda |title=Raimondo to keep schools closed through end of April; online learning will continue |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200330/raimondo-to-keep-schools-closed-through-end-of-april-online-learning-will-continue |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n* '''April 3:''' \n** State beaches and parks closed as of this date, Governor Raimondo cites a lack of social distancing as the reason for the decision.<ref name=\"wpri331\">{{cite web |title=59 hospitalized, 4 more dead in RI due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/march-31-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n** First coronavirus case reported on Block Island.<ref>{{cite web |title=Medical Center: First COVID 19 case diagnosed on Block Island |url=https://www.blockislandtimes.com/node/57128 |website=Block Island Times |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Governor Raimondo announces three field hospitals will be set up in the state to add 1,000 hospital beds in case of hopsital overflow.<ref name=\"wpri43\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 deaths rise to 14 in RI; state setting up makeshift hospitals at three locations |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/april-3-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=3 April 2020 |date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 5:''' The annual Gaspee Days parade and festival, due to take place in [[Pawtuxet Village]] in June, are canceled for 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gaspee Days parade, arts and crafts festival cancelled due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.wpri.com/news/gaspee-days-parade-arts-and-crafts-festival-cancelled-due-to-covid-19/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=5 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 6:'''\n** [[CVS Pharmacy]], which is headquartered in [[Woonsocket, Rhode Island|Woonsocket]], begins a free rapid coronavirus testing program for Rhode Islanders at Twin River Casino in Lincoln.<ref>{{cite web |last1=DaSilva |first1=Melanie |title=CVS Health brings free, rapid COVID-19 testing to RI, will provide 1K more tests per day |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/cvs-health-brings-free-rapid-covid-19-testing-to-ri-provide-1k-more-tests-per-day/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n** The 2020 [[U.S. Senior Open]], scheduled to be held at the [[Newport Country Club]] in Newport in June, is canceled.<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Senior Open at Newport County Club canceled |url=https://www.newportri.com/news/20200406/us-senior-open-at-newport-county-club-canceled |website=The Newport Daily News |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** Rhode Island suprasses 1,000 confirmed cases of coronavirus. As of April 6, there are 1,082 confirmed cases, 109 hospitalized individuals, and 27 deaths in the state.<ref name=\"wpri46\">{{cite web |last1=DaSilva |first1=Melanie |title=2 more die of COVID-19 in RI; cases spike as testing expands |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/april-6-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=6 April 2020 |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 7:''' \n** Providence closes all golf courses and city parks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=List |first1=Madeleine |title=Providence closing all golf courses and parks due to coronavirus |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200407/providence-closing-all-golf-courses-and-parks-due-to-coronavirus |website=Providence Journal |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** Governor Raimondo extends the bans on dine-in service at restaurants and social gatherings of more than five people until May 7. The closure of public recreation, entertainment, and close contact business establishments is also extended to that date.<ref>{{cite web |title=3 deaths, 147 new coronavirus cases in R.I.; ban on gatherings extended to May 8 |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200407/3-deaths-147-new-coronavirus-cases-in-ri-ban-on-gatherings-extended-to-may-8 |website=Providence Journal |accessdate=7 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* '''April 8:''' Governor Raimondo signs an executive order authorizing the Rhode Island Department of Health to fine individuals who deliberately or repeatedly violate quarantine orders after testing positive for coronavirus, coming into close contact with someone diagnosed with coronavirus, or travelling to Rhode Island for a non-work purpose with intent to stay.<ref name=\"projo49\">{{cite web |title=8 deaths, 277 new coronavirus cases in R.I.; state to set fines for violating quarantine orders |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200409/8-deaths-277-new-coronavirus-cases-in-ri-state-to-set-fines-for-violating-quarantine-orders |website=providencejournal.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=8 more COVID-19 deaths in RI; 43 total |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/april-9-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=9 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 9:''' [[Providence College]] moves its graduation commencement ceremony from May 17 to October 31.<ref>{{cite web |title=Providence College pushes commencement ceremony to October |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/providence-college-pushes-commencement-ceremony-to-october |website=WJAR |accessdate=12 April 2020 |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 10:''' Rhode Island surprasses 2,000 confirmed cases of coronavirus. As of April 10, there are 2,015 confirmed cases (including 288 new cases), 169 patients in the hospital, and 49 deaths.<ref>{{cite web |title=6 coronavirus deaths in R.I. as total cases surpass 2,000 |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200410/6-coronavirus-deaths-in-ri-as-total-cases-surpass-2000 |website=The Providence Journal |accessdate=10 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* '''April 11:''' The Rhode Island Turnpike and Bridge Authority closes the eastbound toll collection lanes on the [[Claiborne Pell Newport Bridge]] overnight starting on this date; Overnight westbound tolling had been suspended on March 26. During nighttime hours, bridge traffic is rerouted through open road tolling lanes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Newport Pell Bridge eastbound toll booths hours of operation temporarily change due to reduced travel |url=http://www.ritba.org/sites/default/files/pdf/PressRelease/Toll%20Plaza%20Changes%20Hours%20of%20Operation%20Eastbound%20Press%20Release%20-%20final.pdf |website=Rhode Island Turnpike and Bridge Authority |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 13:''' Rhode Island has its first daily decrease in hospitalizations from coronavirus, with 197 hospitalizations compared to 201 on April 12.<ref name=\"wpri413\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 kills 10 more in RI |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/april-13-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=13 April 2020 |date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 14:''' Rhode Island joins New York, New Jersey, Delaware, Pennsylvania, and Connecticut to form a multi-state council to co-ordinate plans to reopen the economy across the Northeast region once it is safe to do so.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lank |first1=Olivia |title=Govs., including Lamont, join to create plan to reopen economy |url=https://www.wfsb.com/news/gov-lamont-several-other-governors-announce-multi-state-council-for-plan-to-reopen-states/article_b878da7e-7dac-11ea-80f8-93cfcac1c63d.html |website=WFSB |accessdate=19 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* '''April 15:'''\n** Rhode Island Department of Health launches a new statistics website for state coronavirus data.<ref>{{cite web |title=7 more die in RI due to COVID-19 |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/april-15-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> The new website includes, for the first time, cumulative hospital discharges of recovered coronavirus patients.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amaral |first1=Brian |title=One really helpful stat in the state's new COVID data site: Hospital discharges. 168, today's data shows.\u2026https://ri-department-of-health-covid-19-data-rihealth.hub.arcgis.com/ |url=https://twitter.com/bamaral44/status/1250493654357204994 |website=@bamaral44 on Twitter |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=en |date=15 April 2020}}</ref> As of April 15, there have been 168 total discharges since the start of the pandemic.<ref name=\"doh415\">{{cite web |title=RI Department of Health COVID-19 Response Data Hub |url=https://ri-department-of-health-covid-19-data-rihealth.hub.arcgis.com/ |website=ri-department-of-health-covid-19-data-rihealth.hub.arcgis.com |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n** Governor Raimondo announces that residents of border communities, such as [[Tiverton, Rhode Island|Tiverton]], can shop for groceries out of state without having to quarantine for 14 days when they return to Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Richmond |first1=Will |title=Raimondo offers updated guidance for Tiverton, border residents that travel out of state to grocery shop |url=https://www.newportri.com/news/20200415/raimondo-offers-updated-guidance-for-tiverton-border-residents-that-travel-out-of-state-to-grocery-shop |website=The Newport Daily News |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** As of April 15, 66 of the 87 reported deaths in Rhode Island are residents of nursing homes, with 23 deaths recorded at one facility in [[North Providence, Rhode Island|North Providence]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nesi |first1=Ted |title=7 more die in RI due to COVID-19, all but one a nursing home resident |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/april-15-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 18:'''\n** As of this date, Rhode Island workers at customer-facing businesses, manufacturing facilities, and offices will be required to wear masks while on the job.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nesi |first1=Ted |title=RI\u2019s coronavirus death toll rises to 80; many must wear masks as of Saturday |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/april-14-ri-coronavirus-update/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=15 April 2020 |date=14 April 2020}}</ref> Customers at essential retail will also be strongly encouraged to wear masks.<ref name=\"projo414\">{{cite web |last1=Amaral |first1=Brian |title=Seven more die in R.I. from coronavirus; governor orders workers to wear masks |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200414/seven-more-die-in-ri-from-coronavirus-governor-orders-workers-to-wear-masks |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=15 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Workers who cannot do their job while wearing masks, such as call center operators and news reporters, are exempt from the ruling.<ref name=\"projo414\"/> Businesses will not be allowed to turn away customers solely because they are not wearing a mask, except for stores in [[East Providence, Rhode Island|East Providence]] and [[Barrington, Rhode Island|Barrington]], where town laws have made them mandatory.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Amaral |first1=Brian |title=Coronavirus: E. Providence to let stores turn away shoppers without masks |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200418/coronavirus-e-providence-to-let-stores-turn-away-shoppers-without-masks |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Borg |first1=Linda |title=Barrington makes masks mandatory indoors at businesses to fight coronavirus |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200416/barrington-makes-masks-mandatory-indoors-at--businesses-to-fight-coronavirus |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** Special Olympics Rhode Island announces they will hold their summer games virtually in late May; The games had previously been canceled in March.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goggin |first1=Caroline |title=Special Olympics Rhode Island to hold virtual state summer games |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/special-olympics-rhode-island-to-hold-virtual-state-summer-games/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Harvard University]] reports Rhode Island is the only state in the country completing enough coronavirus tests per population - 185 tests per 100,000 residents, above Harvard's recommended 152 per 100,000 residents - to reopen its economy.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nesi |first1=Ted |title=RI is only state doing enough tests to safely reopen, Harvard experts suggest |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/ri-is-only-state-doing-enough-tests-to-safely-reopen-harvard-experts-suggest/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=18 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n** In a conference call with local reporters, Governor Raimondo states she does not plan to extend Rhode Island's stay-at-home order after it expires on May 8.<ref name=\"wpri419\">{{cite web |title=13 new deaths in RI Sunday, bringing total to 150 |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/ri-covid-19-update-sun-apr-19/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Raimondo announces a relief fund for Rhode Island artists, arts and culture workers, and gallery operators.<ref>{{cite web |title=Raimondo announces relief fund for Rhode Island art community |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/raimondo-set-to-give-daily-coronavirus-briefing |website=WJAR |accessdate=19 April 2020 |date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 19:''' Big box stores are required to close their gardening sections to browsing; Sales of gardening items and seeds will continue to be allowed via pick-up, delivery and appointment.<ref name=\"projo418\">{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Paul Edward |title=19 new coronavirus deaths bring R.I. total to 137 as 317 new cases reported |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200418/19-new-coronavirus-deaths-bring-ri-total-to-137-as-317-new-cases-reported |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=18 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* '''April 20:'''\n** Rhode Island surpasses 5,000 coronavirus cases; As of April 20, there are 5,090 confirmed cases and 155 deaths in the state.<ref name=\"projo420\">{{cite web |title=R.I. reports 5 coronavirus deaths; Raimondo lists 6 'key indicators' for reopening economy |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200420/ri-reports-5-coronavirus-deaths-raimondo-lists-6-rsquokey-indicatorsrsquo-for-reopening-economy |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=20 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n** Governor Raimondo announces six key indicators that will determine when Rhode Island will reopen its economy. These are: Whether the spread has continued to decrease in the state, whether the state has supports in place for vulnerable populations and those in quarantine, whether the state healthcare system has the capacity and the [[Personal protective equipment]] to handle another surge, whether large gathering spaces (such as schools and houses of worship) have plans for long-term social distancing, and whether the state is prepare to reimpose measure or close the economy again it is necessary.<ref name=\"projo420\"/>\n* '''April 21:''' The state's first walk-up testing facility opens in Providence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=DaSilva |first1=Melanie |title=State\u2019s first walk-up COVID-19 testing site opens in Providence |url=https://www.wpri.com/health/coronavirus/states-first-walk-up-covid-19-testing-site-opens-in-providence/ |website=WPRI.com |accessdate=21 April 2020 |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n* '''April 22:'''\n** [[Memorial Hospital of Rhode Island|Memorial Hospital]] in [[Pawtucket, Rhode Island|Pawtucket]], which was closed in 2018, is reopened as a testing site for the [[Blackstone Valley]] area.<ref>{{cite web |title=Care New England opens virus testing site at former Memorial Hospital |url=https://turnto10.com/news/local/care-new-england-to-open-virus-testing-site-at-former-memorial-hospital |website=WJAR |accessdate=22 April 2020 |date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n** Governor Raimondo announces she is working with the [[Rhode Island Department of Environmental Management]] on a staggered plan to re-open state parks and beaches as part of the first phase of the state's reopening; The plan would not go into effect until after the state stay-at-home order ends on May 8.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 additional deaths from coronavirus in R.I.; Raimondo says partial reopening of parks, beaches could come in May |url=https://www.providencejournal.com/news/20200422/10-additional-deaths-from-coronavirus-in-ri-raimondo-says-partial-reopening-of-parks-beaches-could-come-in-may |website=providencejournal.com |accessdate=22 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n* '''April 27:''' Garden centers and gardening supply stores will be allowed to reopen.<ref name=\"projo418\"/>\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) Cases in Rhode Island<ref name=\"ri-doh-covid\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Rhode Island Data|url=https://health.ri.gov/data/covid-19/ |website=Department of Health |publisher=State of Rhode Island |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\nUpdated April 22, 2020\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Town\n! scope=\"col\" |Confirmed Cases\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Barrington, Rhode Island|Barrington]]\n|26\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Bristol, Rhode Island|Bristol]]\n|45\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Burrillville, Rhode Isl